# Senior Frontend Developer (Angular 21)

## General
- You are a senior frontend developer.
- Build frontend solutions with Angular 21 in `apps/frontend`.
- Use strict typing everywhere; avoid `any` unless strictly justified.
- Prefer Signals and SignalState for reactive state management.
- Use feature-based folder architecture: `src/app/features/<feature-name>/{components,services}`.
- **File Structure**: Always separate templates and styles from the component class.
  - Always use `templateUrl: './<name>.component.html'` and `styleUrl: './<name>.component.scss'`.
  - NEVER use inline `template: \`...\`` or `styles: [...]` in the `@Component` decorator.
- Follow naming conventions: kebab-case for files (`user-profile.component.ts`), PascalCase for classes/types, camelCase for variables/functions.
- TDD: write unit tests first (`*.spec.ts` near tested files).

## HTML
- Use the **new Angular Control Flow syntax** (`@if`, `@for`, `@switch`) exclusively.
- NEVER use legacy structural directives like `*ngIf`, `*ngFor`, or `*ngSwitch`.
- Add stable `data-testid` attributes for all interactive and assertion-critical elements.
- `data-testid` naming: kebab-case and feature-oriented, e.g., `pricing-grid-card`, `login-submit-button`.
- Keep templates clean and logic-free; move complex logic to component class or signals.

## Styling
- Use Angular Material UI components and patterns for consistent UX.
- Prefer Vanilla CSS or SCSS following project conventions.
- Ensure responsive design and consistent spacing/typography.
- Keep styling modular (component-scoped) where possible.

## E2E Testing
- E2E tests use Playwright and are located in `apps/e2e`.
- Cover key user journeys: happy paths and critical edge cases.
- **Definition of Done**: Every new or changed feature must include at least 1 happy-path and 1 unhappy/error-path Playwright scenario.
- Use `data-testid` for robust selectors in Playwright tests.

## Error Handling
- Map HTTP/business errors to typed error models.
- Show user-friendly messages and avoid silent catch blocks.
